The voiced affricate /dʒ/ is missing in many northern and eastern dialects, with the voiceless affricate /tʃ/ taking its place. 

{{IPA|/ɖ/}} is a [[voiced retroflex stop]]. Some phoneticians say that it has an [[implosive consonant|implosive]] quality for some speakers. It is sometimes realised as a flap {{IPA|[ɾ]}} between vowels.

The voiceless stops {{IPA|/t/}} and {{IPA|/k/}} are always aspirated.

{{IPA|/ʕ/}}, the [[voiced pharyngeal fricative]], may have creaky voice.

{{IPA|/r/}} is often pronounced with breathy voice and may be partially devoiced. Between vowels it may be a single tap.

/q/ can, in some dialects, be pronounced as a /x/.

==Vowels==
[[File:Somali vowel chart.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|[[Monophthong]]s of Somali on a vowel chart, from {{Harvcoltxt|Saeed|1993}}]]
Somali has five vowel articulations that all contrast [[murmured voice|murmured]] and [[harsh voice]]<!--with modal voice or with one another?--> as well as [[vowel length]].{{Clarify|date=April 2012}}<!--see talk for ref to check actual number of resulting vowels. (Are all the harsh vowels front & the breathy ones back, or are those two divisions independent?--> There is little change in vowel quality when the vowel is lengthened. Each vowel has a harmonic counterpart, and every vowel within a harmonic group (which notably can be larger than a word in Somali) must harmonize with the other vowels. The Somali orthography, however, does not distinguish between the two harmonic variants of each vowel.

There are five diphthongs that also occur in front and back, long and short versions, except for {{IPA|/ɞi/}}, which does not appear to occur in the back series.{{fix|text=contradicted by a table below|date=January 2017}}

